---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Contact | burninjurycalc.com';
const description = 'Contact burninjurycalc.com for questions, corrections, or feedback on our burn injury settlement calculator and guides.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Contact</h1>
  <p>Email <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. We're a small team, so email is the only channel we monitor — there's no live chat or phone line, and that's by design: questions after a burn injury deserve a considered written answer, not a rushed one.</p>

  <h2>What we respond to</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Corrections to settlement ranges, TBSA figures, or citations.</strong> Published settlement data and burn-classification standards get updated periodically. If a page cites a figure or citation that's out of date, tell us which page and what the correct figure is; we verify against the primary source — American Burn Association standards, appellate case law, or verdict-tracker data — before making any change.</li>
    <li><strong>Errors or unclear language in guides.</strong> If a sentence in a guide is ambiguous, contradicts itself, or is just hard to follow, we want to know — plain language is one of our core editorial standards.</li>
    <li><strong>Suggestions for new content.</strong> If you searched for a burn-injury compensation question and couldn't find it on the Site — a specific cause, a body-location scenario the calculator doesn't handle — let us know what you were trying to figure out.</li>
    <li><strong>Press and business inquiries.</strong> Journalists covering burn litigation or product-liability fires, and businesses interested in advertising, can reach the same address.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to expect</h2>
  <p>We read every message. Corrections and editorial questions typically get a reply within a few business days. If a correction is verified, we update the affected page and note the date of the material change, consistent with our <a href="/editorial/">corrections policy</a>. We don't always reply to content suggestions individually, but we do track them for future guides.</p>

  <h2>What we don't respond to</h2>
  <p>We can't evaluate your specific burn, tell you what your case is actually worth, or review a settlement offer — that requires an attorney who has seen your medical records and the facts of how the burn occurred. We also can't give medical guidance about your treatment or recovery; that's a conversation for your treating burn-center team. We don't recommend specific attorneys, law firms, or burn centers, and don't accept payment to feature or promote anyone on the Site. If you email us asking for case-specific advice, we'll point you back to this policy and to the guidance below.</p>

  <h2>Before you email</h2>
  <p>Many questions we get are already answered on the Site: check the <a href="/faq/">FAQ</a> for common questions on settlement timing, expert witnesses, and taxation, or the <a href="/guides/">guides</a> — including <a href="/guides/what-to-do-after-a-burn-injury/">what to do after a burn injury</a>, <a href="/guides/burn-classifications-and-prognosis/">burn classifications and prognosis</a>, and <a href="/guides/common-burn-injury-claim-misconceptions/">common burn injury claim misconceptions</a>. If your question is about how the calculator arrived at a number, the <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a> walks through the six damages components and the location and cause multipliers in detail, with a worked example.</p>

  <h2>If you actually need an attorney</h2>
  <p>We don't make referrals, but a few things are worth knowing before you search. Burn cases are unusual among personal injury matters because liability often extends beyond ordinary negligence: a defective lithium battery, a faulty appliance, or an unsafe consumer product can support a product-liability claim against a manufacturer with substantial insurance coverage, while a landlord's missing smoke detectors or an unsafely maintained rental property can support a premises-liability claim in addition to any general negligence theory. A general-practice personal injury attorney may not immediately recognize which of these theories applies, or may not have relationships with the product-liability or fire-cause experts a strong claim often requires. Look specifically for attorneys or firms that describe themselves as handling burn injuries, product liability, or catastrophic injury litigation. Because severe burn cases also depend on specialized burn-unit medical documentation — TBSA measured against the Lund-Browder chart rather than a rough field estimate, a clear record of the reconstructive-surgery timeline, and burn-center attending testimony on prognosis — an attorney experienced in burn litigation will know what to request from the treatment team early, before records are harder to obtain. Most burn-injury attorneys offer a free initial consultation and work on contingency, so cost isn't a reason to delay that first call. If you'd rather start from a neutral referral source, your state bar association's lawyer referral service can point you to attorneys who handle burn and product-liability cases in your area.</p>
</BaseLayout>
